{{Use American English|date=May 2016}} {{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}} The '''Drone Papers''' is a leak of national security documents published by ''[[The Intercept]]'' in October 2015 on the United States's use of [[drone strike|drone warfare]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2015/10/drama-of-the-drone-papers.html|title=The Drama of the Drone Papers|work=Daily Intelligencer|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2015/10/16/precisely_wrong_faulty_intelligence_drives_civilian|title="The Drone Papers" Reveals How Faulty Intel &amp; Secret "Kill Chain" Mark Suspects, Civilians for Death - Democracy Now!|work=Democracy Now!|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.newsweek.com/leaked-documents-reveal-new-details-about-uss-lethal-drone-programs-383949 |title=Leaked Documents Reveal New Details About the U.S.’s Lethal Drone Programs |first=Lauren |last=Walker |work=Newsweek |date=October 15, 2015 |accessdate=July 13, 2017}}.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rt.com/usa/318767-obama-drones-papers-leak/|title=Leaked: 'New Snowden' releases Obama's drone program papers|work=RT International|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> The leak revealed the bureaucratic process of approving a drone strike.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.democracynow.org/2015/10/22/where_does_this_end_after_drone|title="Where Does This End?": After Drone Papers Leaks, U.K. Gov't Has a Kill List of Its Own|work=Democracy Now!|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref>
== Response == [[Micah Zenko]] of ''[[Foreign Policy]]'' wrote that the Drone Papers "mandate a Congressional investigation" but did not expect one to happen during the Obama administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2015/10/15/the-intercepts-drone-papers-revelations-mandate-a-congressional-investigation/|title=The Intercept’s ‘Drone Papers’ Revelations Mandate a Congressional Investigation|first=Micah |last=Zenko|date=October 15, 2015|work=Foreign Policy|accessdate=May 6, 2016}}</ref> ''The Guardian'' wrote that the documents showed that close to 90 percent of United States drone killings in a five-month period did not kill the intended target.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/10/a-second-snowden-leaks-a-mother-lode-of-drone-docs/|title=A Second Snowden Has Leaked a Mother Lode of Drone Docs|publisher=}}</ref>
