{{infobox person | name = Phiwa Nkambule | image = Phiwayinkosi Sicelo Nkambule.png | alt = Phiwa Nkambule | caption = | birth_name = Sicelo Phiwayinkosi Nkambule | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1992|01|24}} | birth_place = [[Manzini, Swaziland|Manzini]] | residence = | education = {{plainlist| *[[Cefups Academy]] *[[University of Pretoria]] *[[University of South Africa]] *[[CFA Institute]] }} | alma_mater = <!--Only higher education; not used when it is misleading about the subject's attendance/graduation, e.g. Phiwa Nkambule withdrew from the University of Pretoria so don't add it here.--> | occupation = {{plainlist| *[[Internet Entrepreneur]] *[[Software Engineer]] *[[Businessperson]] }} | title = Co-founder & CEO of [[Riovic]] | years_active = 2013–present | home_town = | salary = | net_worth = | spouse = | children = | relatives = | website = | signature = | known = {{plainlist| *[[Financial Technology]] *[[Peer-to-peer insurance|Crowdfunded Insurance]] }} }} '''Phiwa Nkambule''' (born January 24, 1992) is an [[internet entrepreneur]] best known for co-founding and leading [[Riovic]] as its [[chief executive officer]].<ref name=forbesafrica>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbesafrica.com/30-under-30/2018/06/04/under-30-technology/|title=Under 30 Technology - Forbes Africa|date=4 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref>
==Early life== Phiwa Nkambule was born in [[Manzini, Swaziland|Manzini]] where he also spent his childhood.<ref name=PR20180503>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/swaziland/swazi-observer/20180503/281990378145647|title=Eswatini Born Entrepreneur Develops FinTech Platform|date=3 May 2018|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=observer>{{cite web|url=http://new.observer.org.sz/details.php?id=5348|title=First Liswati Makes it to Forbes List|website=new.observer.org.sz}}</ref> In 2006, as a 14-year-old, he began fixing and building computers with his uncle in a small township in Swaziland.<ref name=forbesafrica/> Nkambule moved to South Africa in 2007 for academic purposes.<ref name=PR20160709>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/swaziland/observer-on-saturday/20160709/281805693258766|title=Swazi Born Entrepreneur Making Waves in SA Insurance Industry|date=9 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref> Phiwa was a [[law student]] at the [[University of Pretoria]] before quitting to start his first technology company [[Cybatar]] from his garage in 2014.<ref name=themoneyfam>{{cite web|url=http://www.themoneyfam.com/fintech-entrepreneur-peer-investing/|title=Why this 25 Year Old Fintech Entrepreneur Thinks Your Peers are Your Biggest Investments|date=18 May 2017|publisher=}}</ref> It was at the university where he taught himself web and app development.<ref name=forbesafrica/>
==Entrepreneurship==
Before leaving the [[University of Pretoria]] Phiwa attempted to work with the Swaziland National Library and the Manzini Regional Education Office in 2013 but was rejected.<ref name=PR20180606>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/swaziland/swazi-observer/20180606/281625305995026|title=Forbes listed Liswati rejected by his own country|date=6 June 2018|publisher=}}</ref> After dropping out of university in 2014 Nkambule founded [[Cybatar]], a technology company focused on fuel delivery from his garage in [[Pretoria]], South Africa.<ref name=forbesafrica/><ref name=itweb1>{{cite web|url=https://www.itweb.co.za/content/lP3gQ2MG2mw7nRD1|title=SA start-up uses crowdfunding for insurance|first=ITWeb, Paula|last=Gilbert|date=13 May 2016|publisher=}}</ref><ref name=howwemadeitinafrica>{{cite web|url=https://www.howwemadeitinafrica.com/swaziland-born-entrepreneur-introduces-crowdfunded-insurance/54932/|title=Swaziland-born entrepreneur introduces crowdfunded insurance|date=1 July 2016|publisher=}}</ref>
In 2015 Nkambule co-founded [[Riovic]], an [[Fintech|insurance technology]] company.<ref name=forbesafrica/><ref name=observer/><ref name=PR20180503/><ref name=PR20160709/><ref name=PR20180606/><ref name=themoneyfam/> The company owns and operates online platforms that connect consumers with insurance, credit and investments.<ref name="bloomberg.com">{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=327840719|title=Riovic Corporation: Private Company Information - Bloomberg|website=www.bloomberg.com}}</ref> He was invited to deliver a keynote address on Digital Technologies in Insurance at the 13th International Microinsurance Conference in Peru, South America in November 2017.<ref name=PR20180503/><ref name=observer/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.munichre-foundation.org/home/Microinsurance/common/Microinsurance_Archive/2017IMC/Report/Plenary_4.html|title=Munich Re Foundation - Contact|website=www.munichre-foundation.org}}</ref><ref name="bloomberg.com"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://a2ii.org/en/report/workshops-and-seminars-event-reports-presentations-latin-america-digital-technology/what-does|title=What does the Fourth Industrial Revolution hold for Insurance? - Access to Insurance|website=a2ii.org}}</ref>
==Philanthropy== On 24 October 2015 he released the first tuition crowdfunding platform in South Africa in the wake of the [[FeesMustFall]] protests that saw the country's tertiary institutions shutdown to help save students from tuition debt.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.htxt.co.za/2015/10/28/crowdfunding-site-launched-to-help-500-sa-students-cover-tuition-fees-by-end-of-2015/|title=Crowdfunding site launched to help 500 SA students cover tuition fees by end of 2015 - htxt.africa|date=28 October 2015|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.itweb.co.za/content/ALPwQ57lWbDvNgkj|title=Crowdfunding to aid #FeesMustFall campaign|last=Mzekandaba|first=Simnikiwe|date=2015-10-28|work=ITWeb|access-date=2018-11-08|language=en-ZA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://ventureburn.com/2015/10/crowdfunding-platform-edufund-seeks-to-save-sa-students-from-tuition-debt/|title=Crowdfunding platform EduFund seeks to save SA students from tuition debt – Ventureburn|date=26 October 2015|publisher=}}</ref> He also launched a free online learning platform for digital skills aimed at reducing youth unemployment rate in South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizcommunity.com/Article/196/659/165447.html|title=Free online academic institution launched|website=www.bizcommunity.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.smesouthafrica.co.za/17459/Top-Entrepreneurship-and-Business-Stories/|title=Today's Top Entrepreneurship and Business Stories (7 August)|first=Staff|last=Writer|date=7 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://social-tv.co.za/?p=868|title=FREE ONLINE ACADEMIC INSTITUTION LAUNCHED - Social TV|website=social-tv.co.za}}</ref>
==Awards and recognition== In June 2018, Phiwa Nkambule was named in the [[Forbes 30 Under 30|Forbes Africa 30 Under 30]] list of most promising entrepreneurs in the technology category.<ref name=forbesafrica/> In October he was named in [[Destiny Man]]’s Power of 40 list, a list of 40 trailblazers under the age of 40.<ref>http://www.pressreader.com/south-africa/destiny-man/20181201/282716227967510</ref>
